shire, England":"Worleston, Cheshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","of Worleston, Cheshire, England":"Worleston, Cheshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"Abt 1237–":"about 1237–Deceased","1239–1265":"1239–1265","1262–1299":"1262–1299","1264–Female":"1264–Deceased","1237–Male":"1237–Deceased","1239":"1239","ABT 1261":"about 1261","Abt 1262":"about 1262","1237":"1237","ABT 1264":"about 1264","1299":"1299","1265":"1265","1264":"1264","Abt 1237":"about 1237","1262":"1262","Worleston, Cheshire, England":"Worleston, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","of Worleston, Cheshire, England":"Worleston, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Coudray","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Channel Islands:  see  Cowdrey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Cowdrey","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): habitational name from Coudrai in Seine-Maritime, France, or Coudray in Eure, France, or from Cowdray or Cowdry in Sussex, England. The latter was probably named after one of the places in France. All are named with Old French <i>coudraie</i> ‘hazel copse’ (a collective noun from <i>coudre</i> ‘hazelnut tree’, Late Latin <i>colurus</i>, a metathesized form of classical Latin <i>corylus</i>, from Greek <i>korylos</i>). Alternatively, but less likely, a topographic name from Old French <i>coudraie</i> ‘hazel copse’, adopted into English, denoting someone who lived near a hazel copse."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Pet form of any of the given names beginning with the letter <i>D-</i> (  compare  Jay   and   Kay  ), in particular   Dorothy .  It is also used as an independent name, and may in some cases be associated with the River Dee (  compare  Clyde  )."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Robert de Coudray was born about 1237, in Worleston, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom. He married Lady Matilda de Coudray about 1261. They were the parents of at least 2 daughters."},"et":{"Abt 1237–":"umbes 1237–Surnud","1239–1265":"1239–1265","1262–1299":"1262–1299","1264–Female":"1264–Surnud","1237–Male":"1237–Surnud","1239":"1239","ABT 1261":"umbes 1261","Abt 1262":"umbes 1262","1237":"1237","ABT 1264":"umbes 1264","1299":"1299","1265":"1265","1264":"1264","Abt 1237":"umbes 1237","1262":"1262","Worleston, Cheshire, England":"Worleston, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","of Worleston, Cheshire, England":"Worleston, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1237–":"noin 1237–Kuollut","1239–1265":"1239–1265","1262–1299":"1262–1299","1264–Female":"1264–Kuollut","1237–Male":"1237–Kuollut","1239":"1239","ABT 1261":"noin 1261","Abt 1262":"noin 1262","1237":"1237","ABT 1264":"noin 1264","1299":"1299","1265":"1265","1264":"1264","Abt 1237":"noin 1237","1262":"1262","Worleston, Cheshire, England":"Worleston, Cheshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskun